body:
Closes #279

Please see discussion there. Here is merely a brief copy of the discussion there.

What it achieves (example):

```
    let a = Mat::new_rows_cols_with_default(2, 3, CV_8UC1, 100.0.into())?;
    let b = Mat::new_rows_cols_with_default(2, 3, CV_8UC1, 10.0.into())?;
    let c = Mat::new_rows_cols_with_default(2, 3, CV_8UC1, 50.0.into())?;
    let d = Mat::new_rows_cols_with_default(2, 3, CV_8UC1, 2.0.into())?;
    let x = (&a / d - &b + &c / 2.0f64 - Scalar::from(10f64))
        .into_result()?
        .to_mat()?;
    println!("x={:?}", x.data_bytes());
```

Notice that it:

* handles error. only one `.into_result()?` after *finishing all* chained operators is enough. no need for verbose `?` after each math operation, such as `(((a+b)?+c)?+d)?`.
* handles Mat, MatExpr, Scalar, f64 and interaction between them
* handles both Something and &Something (e.g. Mat and &Mat; MatExpr and &MatExpr). If only handles Mat but no &Mat, after math operations your original Mat can never be reused, which is awful. If only handles &Mat but no Mat, you have to write `&(&(a+b)+c)+d` and so on, which is still too verbose.
